{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514177"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12288"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12288"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.15,0.14,0.47,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4810"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51320"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4810"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12288"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36609"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"240"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14730"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51320"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of severe epigastric and chest pain. These symptoms came on after a meal at a restaurant, where he consumed several glasses of wine, felt nauseated and then vomited. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes for which he takes metformin. On examination, he looks unwell, with a blood pressure of 100/70 mmHg, pulse 115/min, temperature 37.2\u00b0C and respiratory rate 25/min. On auscultation, breath sounds are decreased at the right lung base. His abdomen is mildly tender in the epigastrium, and the rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic dissection","Diaphragmatic rupture","Acute pancreatitis","Oesophageal perforation","Mallory-Weiss tear"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is a traumatic (barogenic) \u003Cstrong\u003Eperforation of the oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E. Otherwise known as Boerhaave\u0027s syndrome, the perforation is the result of increased intra-oesophageal pressure caused by vomiting or retching against a closed glottis. It is common in a scenario of over-indulgence of food or alcohol. Pathognomonic features are the presence of subcutaneous emphysema, with crepitus felt on palpation of the chest and neck (although this can take time to develop), Hamman\u0027s sign of a \u0027crunching\u0027 sound on cardiac auscultation, and a hydropneumothorax on chest radiography.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECardiac causes should always be considered in patients with severe chest pain. \u003Cstrong\u003EAortic dissection\u003C/strong\u003E presents with severe chest/back pain with widened mediastinum but is more common at an older age and in patients with cardiac risk factors (hypertension, preexisting aortic aneurysm) or in younger patients with connective tissue disorders. This patient is not hypertensive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiaphragmatic rupture\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after blunt thoracoabdominal trauma due to a sudden and unequal increase in pressure. The chest X-ray typically reveals an elevated hemidiaphragm or migration of abdominal contents into the thoracic cavity rather than pleural effusion, as is evident in this case. It can only occur spontaneously in patients with a pre-existing injury to the diaphragm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pain associated with \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E tends to be primarily abdominal, of more gradual onset, and there would usually be more obvious epigastric tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMallory-Weiss syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E presents with haemetemesis - bringing up fresh blood after an episode of vomiting. It is due to a submucosal tear and the oesophageal wall remains intact, with no pleural accumulation of material - as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Boerhaave\u0027s syndrome is a surgical emergency, requiring rapid resuscitation, antibiotics and usually major emergency surgery to prevent further leakage"],"references":["Allaway M GR, Morris PD, Sinclair J-L B, et al.  Management of Boerhaave syndrome in Australasia: a retrospective case series and systematic review of the Australasian literature. ANZ J Surg 2021; 91:1376\u201384. Available at:  https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33319446/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36609"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12288"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18554"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18554"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/891d956d-60b8-40c6-88d2-088dcd401937.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/891d956d-60b8-40c6-88d2-088dcd401937.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":619,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36609"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-23T22:26:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-23T22:27:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4810"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"quest